Issues.Body:
### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

common

### Description

I think it would be a great addition to the type-safety of templates if `@switch` were checked to be exhaustive.

Currently, if you have a field with 3 possible values:

```ts
type UserType = 'admin' | 'logged' | 'anonymous'
```

and then use a `@switch` in the template:

```html
@switch (userType) {
  @case ('admin') {
    Hello admin
  }
  @case ('logged') {
    Hello user
  }
}
```

the template compiles just fine, whereas the `'anonymous'` case is not covered.

### Proposed solution

It would be great to get a compiler error if a case is missing (when no default is provided of course). 

TypeScript would complain about a missing case, if the switch was used to return a value in a function:

```ts
function s(userType: UserType): boolean {
  switch (userType) {
    case 'admin': return true;
    case 'logged': return true;
  }
}
```

The generated TCB could maybe be code along those lines instead of a "simple" switch?

### Alternatives considered

I don't think we can work around that easily?

### Which @angular/* package(s) are relevant/related to the feature request?

common

### Description

Currently, the control flow syntax only allows to alias the first if condition.
It would be handy to be able to alias the `else if` blocks as well:

```html
@if (condition1; as condition1Result) {
  Hello1 {{ condition1Result }}
} @else if (condition2; as condition2Result) {
  Hello2 {{ condition2Result }}
} @else {
  Default
}
```


Throws:
```
NG5002: "as" expression is only allowed on the primary @if block [plugin angular-compiler]

    src/app/app.component.html:3:24:
      3 │ } @else if (condition2; as condition2Result) {
        ╵                         ~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
```

It looks like this was implemented then reverted but the reasons are not clearly explained (https://github.com/angular/angular/commit/eb1faa8f87edc6ddd9dd855752a3b2b8a626b09b)

### Proposed solution

`@else if` blocks could allow aliasing the condition

### Alternatives considered

It's possible to work around that by using nested `@if`, but it's a bit sad as we now have `else if`:

```html
@if (condition1; as condition1Result) {
  Hello1 {{ condition1Result }}
} @else {
  @if (condition2; as condition2Result) {
    Hello2 {{ condition2Result }}
  } @else {
    Default
  }
}
```

There was a sublte bug in the previous implementation. Consider the case:

```scss
div {
  @include current-selector-or-root() {
    color: red;
  }
  color: green;
}
```

The previous implementation lifted the `color: red;` into a separate selector block that came *after* the initial one, resulting in the order being flipped:

```css
div {
  color: green;
}
div {
  color: red;
}
```

The new code will produce the correct ordering:

```css
div {
  color: red;
  color: green;
}
```
